post_text:
Due to the uncertainty of forecasted weather conditions for much of South Louisiana, Livingston Parish Public Schools will remain closed tomorrow (Wednesday, Aug. 26), School Superintendent Joe Murphy announced.

Murphy said school officials will review weather conditions on Wednesday to determine plans for the remainder of the week.

Hurricane Laura is forecast to be a Category 3 storm, with effects being felt as early as Wednesday morning along the Louisiana-Texas coast. It is expected to bring much wind damage, heavy rainfall, and potential flash floods in its path.

Murphy said school officials will continue to work closely with state and local Homeland Security and Emergency Preparedness officials to get the latest information on weather conditions for the area.

The latest information from the school district can also be found at www.lpsb.org.

Murphy said the district will announce its plans to parents by Tuesday afternoon.

Currently, schools are closed through Tuesday, Aug. 25, due to weather safety concerns that may be caused Tropical Storm Marco. Tropical Storm Laura is expected to make landfall on Tuesday evening. Updates on that storm system will determine the districtâ€™s schedule for the remainder of the week.

Gracias por trabajar con nosotros para educar a nuestros estudiantes.

post_text:
Livingston Parish Public Schools Maintenance Department is taking applications for the position of a Journeyman Electrician at the Central Office, The qualifications are: High School Graduate or GED equivalent, extensive knowledge in single phase, three phase, and 277 volt systems. Formal training is required as well as five (5) years' experience in residential, commercial and industrial electrical work. Must also have hot work experience. Requirements include using man-lift equipment, ladders and other equipment required to perform all electrical task. Licensed electrician and experience with educational facilities preferred. Must have a valid LA driver's license and a clean driving record, willingness to work callouts, weekends and holidays. Preferred experience in commercial and educational facilities. Starting salary for this position is $32, 844.00 plus benefits. Applications will be accepted through 12:00 PM, Thursday, August 20, 2020. If you have any questions please contact Steve Vampran, Human Resource Supervisor.
To apply, go to https://phl.applitrack.com/lpsb/onlineapp/

shared_text:
Dream Teachers
June 1 at 6:30 AM Â·

Congratulations to our June Teacher of the Month, Misty Reynerson! Mrs. Misty Reynerson teaches English Language Arts at Live Oak Middle School. She is also a sponsor of Beta Club and Chess Club. Her credentials include a Bachelor's degree in Elementary Education, a Master's degree in Special Education, and an Academically Gifted certification. She has been teaching for 22 years. Mrs. Reynerson began her career teaching third grade, followed by two years of middle school French, before transferring to Livingston parish to teach academically gifted students in 2001. She has been at Live Oak Middle school for nineteen years, where she has spent the past five years teaching English Language Arts to sixth-graders. Mrs. Reynerson is married to Michael Reynerson, and they have two children named Grace and Cole. In her spare time, Mrs. Reynerson enjoys spending time with her family and reading, and she is very grateful to have a job that allows her to share her love of literature with her students.

post_text: Under the new Pandemic EBT (P-EBT) program, families of children who normally receive free meals at school get may get financial assistance to replace those meals. Pâ€‘EBT benefits are available for Pre-K through 12th grade students currently enrolled in LPPS. Families must complete the online application to receive benefits. The online application is available now through June 7 at https://pebt.doe.louisiana.gov/PublicApps/SNP/. Applicants must provide the full name of the student and parent, date of birth, Social Security number, home address, school and school district on their application. Without the requested information, the Department of Children and Family Services cannot issue the Electronic Benefit Transfer (EBT) card and provide benefits. YOU DO NOT NEED TO CONTACT THE SCHOOL OR SCHOOL SYSTEM TO RECEIVE THIS SERVICE. Additional information and answers to frequently asked questions can be found at http://www.dcfs.louisiana.gov/page/pebt-program#faq.

In an effort to prepare to better support our school communities, Livingston Parish Public Schools is conducting an access survey for all the households with school age students in the district. We are asking that each household fills out this very important survey. The information gathered will allow the district to plan for appropriate support for all our communities. It will also give us information that will help us better leverage Federal, State, and Local governmental supports.
Access the survey at this link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/N2D2Z7M

Only ONE answer per household is necessary.
shared_text:
SURVEYMONKEY.COM
Home Access Survey
text:
In an effort to prepare to better support our school communities, Livingston Parish Public Schools is conducting an access survey for all the households with school age students in the district. We are asking that each household fills out this very important survey. The information gathered will allow the district to plan for appropriate support for all our communities. It will also give us information that will help us better leverage Federal, State, and Local governmental supports.
Access the survey at this link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/N2D2Z7M

Only ONE answer per household is necessary.

SURVEYMONKEY.COM
Home Access Survey

Parents and Guardians,
Each school in our district has created blended learning opportunities and resources for students to remain engaged during this time away from campus. Many schools offer live or recorded instruction through Zoom, Loom, FlipGrid, or YouTube. Online lessons and activities are sometimes provided through Google Classroom or email. You are encouraged to follow guidance from the administration and teachers from your childâ€™s school when planning the activities and lessons to be completed each day. This document includes many
resources available to our students. Feel free to use these resources to compliment or enrich, not to replace, what is being assigned by the school.
Thank you for supporting your students in their time away from us.

This document, in both English and Spanish can be found under our Digital Help Tab, or you can click the link below.
Link: www.lpsb.org/UserFiles/Servers/Server_546/File/DIGITAL%20HELP/LPPS%20Academic%20Resources%20COVID%2019.pdf

Governor Edwards has issued a letter requesting suspension of educational policies. These are suspensions of policies impacting the following processes related to education: Testing Administration, School and District Accountability, Teacher Evaluation and Credentialing, Student Attendance, Teacher Work Days, Charter School Application and Enrollment. These suspensions are the result of collaboration between multiple state agencies that are referenced in the letter. Additionally some of these suspensions are dependent on USDOE's waiver of certain provisions of ESSA.
Please note that this is NOT a proclamation and at this point in time, a request only.

Congratulations to Amanda Jones from Live Oak Middle for being included in the national School Library Journal. Thanks for working so hard.

"Reaching out to authors via social media can be as simple as tagging them in conversations on Twitter or in booktalks or book reviews on Twitter, Instagram, Facebook, or YouTube. Sharing book reviews by young readers can also be an opportunity to connect them with the authors of books they love, as Amanda Jones, librarian at Live Oak Middle School in Denham Springs, LA, does. Her students recommend a book each week, and she shares those recommendations on Twitter.

â€œ[W]e do booktalks on Tuesdays, and I tag the authors. When they retweet or like a post, I print it out and hang it in the library and give the kids a copy,â€ she said on Twitter. Jones facilitates the interaction between students and the authors."

Your immediate attention to this matter is requested.

It's called the Tripping Jump Challenge and it started from the video app, Tik Tok.

It works like this: Three people line up, and when the person in the middle jumps, the other two kick the person's legs from under him or her.

This can cause serious injuries to the target middle jumper such as broken bones, concussions and worse.

We ask that you notify your staff about this challenge and have your PE coaches educate each class on the dangers of this activity and that participation in this behavior will not be tolerated and will result in disciplinary action.
text:
Your immediate attention to this matter is requested.

It's called the Tripping Jump Challenge and it started from the video app, Tik Tok.

It works like this: Three people line up, and when the person in the middle jumps, the other two kick the person's legs from under him or her.

This can cause serious injuries to the target middle jumper such as broken bones, concussions and worse.

We ask that you notify your staff about this challenge and have your PE coaches educate each class on the dangers of this activity and that participation in this behavior will not be tolerated and will result in disciplinary action.

In Livingston Parish, we strive to give students every opportunity to experience and access science, technology, engineering, art, and math (STEAM) with the goal of promoting educational and career opportunities. To further our goal of STEAM education in the district, we are hosting our inaugural STEAM Expo on March 7 of 2020 for the entire surrounding community from 9:00 a.m. -2:00 p.m. This STEAM Expo will be held at the Denham Springs High School STEM and Robotics Center in partnership with LPPS and Livingston Parish Literacy and Technology Center.
The STEAM Expo will provide engaging displays and activities to increase student and parent awareness and interest in STEAM education and careers while providing opportunities to support school and community initiatives.
If you are a business or school and would like to participate in this community project, it is not too late! Please contact Nikki Lavergne at Nikki.Lavergne@lpsb.org.

ALL PARENTS MUST BRING A CERTIFIED BIRTH CERTIFICATE, SOCIAL SECURITY CARD, COMPLETE IMMUNIZATION RECORD, AND FOUR (4) PROOFS OF RESIDENCE TO REGISTER THEIR CHILD.

post_text: We have great things happening all over the district. Check out this amazing opportunity for students at Live Oak Middle!
shared_text:
LOM Library
February 7 at 3:42 PM Â·

Today was AWESOME! Several of our ELA classes got to meet Karen Land, an Iditarod racer, writer, and wilderness advocate, and her dogs Noggin and Chloe for their unit on animal/human allies. We learned that the Iditarod is approximately 1049 miles, can take over 10 days, and requires a lot of endurance (and clothing). Several students got to try on gear! Did you know a sled and the dogs can be as long as a basketball court? For more information on Karen Land and the Iditarod, visit https://www.lomlibrary.org/author-visits--interactions.html. Want to check out books that inspired her? We have Dogsong and Woodsong by Gary Paulson available for checkout.

In Livingston Parish, we strive to give students every opportunity to experience and access science, technology, engineering, art, and math (STEAM) with the goal of promoting educational and career opportunities.

In partnership with the Denham Springs STEM and Robotics Center and the Livingston Parish Literacy and Technology Center, we are hosting our first ever STEAM Expo to work toward our goal of promoting STEAM education in the district!

The STEAM Expo will be held at the Denham Springs STEM and Robotics Center on March 6th and 7th. We are currently looking for businesses, organizations, and clubs to join us in this amazing experience by providing activities, displays, giveaways, and/or exhibits. If you or someone you know is interested in collaborating with us, please click the link below: https://is.gd/zdl4Od

As always, please SHARE!

Thank you for your consideration!

Reflex Math sponsored a contest "Reflex Turkey Trot" October 31st through November 28th. The teachers had their students working to achieve the highest green light percentage, the highest average total usage, and the total facts answered. Also, the contest included a "Twitter Challenge" looking for teachers to post pictures of their Reflex Math bulletin boards. The Reflex Math prize patrol visited the school campuses on December 13th.

The top 3 winners with 15+ students:
Jennifer Levert - Springfield Elementary
Mary Tournillon -Springfield Elementary
Sealy Petavino - North Live Oak

Top winner with less than 15 students:
Stephanie Stewart - Southside Elementary

Twitter winner:
Sommer Wadsworth- North Corbin Elementary

The Career and Tech Education department is hosting multiple night classes around the district for high school students.

Classes include Baking & Pastry (dually enrolled through NorthShore Technical Community College), Flying Unmanned Aircraft Systems (Drones), Carpentry I, Electrical I, Welding II, Scaffolding, and Operation Spark I (Introduction to Coding).

Upon successful completion, students will earn Carnegie Credit, industry based-certification (if applicable), and a bonus of $300 for attaining industry-based certification (if applicable). Students will be notified via email if they are accepted into the program no later than January 3, 2020.
Registration open 12/3 â€“ 12/16.
Questions? Contact Brandi.Desselle@lpsb.org

post_text:
Denham Venom Robotics is looking for friends and family that may be a mechanical engineer, an electrician, a project manager or an electrical engineer. Maybe you know someone who is retired and looking for things to do with their time. There is so much knowledge that people learn just from engaging in amazing careers from whom the students would benefit!

Hours are negotiable but we generally ask volunteers to come in for three to four hours, two to three days per week from January through March. Mentors will be working with small groups of students who are building or designing different sub-systems of our robot or working on awards submissions and creating media documents.
Interested? Want more information, please submit the volunteer form at this link: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/JM62FYN

post_text: The administration and faculty of Livingston Parish Schools are aware of the community reaction to the Attorney Generalâ€™s investigation of a former teacher in our district. In compliance with the wishes of the Attorney General and to protect the integrity of the investigation and the privacy of our students and their families, LPPS will not comment or discuss details of the matter until such time as the case has reached disposition. Our priority is the welfare of the children of this district and the preservation of a consistent, quality educational process during this stressful time. Thank you for your continued support.

post_text:
This Saturday, August 24th, Denham High School Robotics club will be hosting the Dow Red Stick Rumble. It is the first ever Competitive Robotics Event in Livingston Parish.
ADMISSION IS FREE and OPEN TO THE PUBLIC!

Please invite your family and your students to join us on Planet Primus where thirty robots, each weighing in at over 135 pounds, and some standing over eight feet tall will be competing against one another. Teams from Louisiana, Texas, and Mississippi will be there.

The event will take place at the Hornsby Gym at Denham High from 8AM till 5PM.

The Dow Red Stick Rumble is an amazing opportunity for students of all ages and grade levels to see real robots up close and personal. They can tour the pits and see how robots are built and watch games being played on the gym floor.
